1
00:05:25,238 --> 00:05:27,433
We're just about ready
to go here.

2
00:05:27,474 --> 00:05:28,532
Good.

3
00:05:28,575 --> 00:05:31,544
I'm looking for James.
Has anybody seen James Ballard?

4
00:05:31,578 --> 00:05:34,877
Do you know who I mean?
The producer of this epic?

5
00:05:34,914 --> 00:05:36,779
I think I saw him
in the camera room.

6
00:05:42,589 --> 00:05:44,216
James, are you in there?

7
00:05:45,759 --> 00:05:50,253
Can we get your stamp of
approval on our steadicam shot?

8
00:05:54,634 --> 00:05:55,658
Of course.

9
00:05:59,973 --> 00:06:01,907
Be there in a minute.

10
00:06:12,385 --> 00:06:14,080
Where were you?

11
00:06:16,723 --> 00:06:18,918
In a private aircraft hangar.

12
00:06:21,561 --> 00:06:23,961
Anyone could've walked in.

13
00:06:25,432 --> 00:06:27,263
Did you come?

14
00:06:28,935 --> 00:06:29,924
No.

15
00:06:34,774 --> 00:06:38,938
What about your camera girl?
Did she come?

16
00:06:54,294 --> 00:06:56,285
We were interrupted.

17
00:07:01,901 --> 00:07:04,392
I had to go back to the set.

18
00:07:07,073 --> 00:07:08,665
Poor darling.

19
00:07:14,080 --> 00:07:15,809
Maybe the next one.

20
00:07:18,752 --> 00:07:20,481
Maybe the next one.

21
00:07:58,291 --> 00:07:59,451
Shit.

22
00:09:34,754 --> 00:09:36,745
Not a lot of action here.

23
00:09:38,758 --> 00:09:42,091
Have you considered this
would be the airport hospital?

24
00:09:44,264 --> 00:09:46,926
This ward is reserved
for air crash victims.

25
00:09:49,435 --> 00:09:51,300
The beds are kept waiting.

26
00:09:52,205 --> 00:09:54,696
Well, if I ground it during
my flying lesson Saturday...

27
00:09:54,741 --> 00:09:57,266
you might wake up
and find me next to you.

28
00:09:59,312 --> 00:10:01,610
You're getting out of bed soon.

29
00:10:03,149 --> 00:10:04,980
They want you to walk.

30
00:10:12,492 --> 00:10:14,323
The other man, the dead man?

31
00:10:15,328 --> 00:10:16,818
His wife's a doctor.

32
00:10:18,164 --> 00:10:20,291
Dr. Helen Remington.

33
00:10:20,333 --> 00:10:23,894
She's here somewhere...
as a patient, of course.

34
00:10:25,571 --> 00:10:27,596
Maybe you'll find her
in the hallways...

35
00:10:27,640 --> 00:10:29,335
during one of your walks.

36
00:10:31,010 --> 00:10:32,875
And her husband, what was he?

37
00:10:35,848 --> 00:10:38,544
A chemical engineer
for a food company.

38
00:10:42,255 --> 00:10:44,519
Where's... where's the car?

39
00:10:46,092 --> 00:10:48,583
Outside, in the visitors
car park.

40
00:10:48,628 --> 00:10:49,856
What?

41
00:10:52,265 --> 00:10:53,994
They brought the car here?

42
00:10:54,033 --> 00:10:56,661
My car. Not yours.

43
00:11:00,073 --> 00:11:02,337
Yours is a complete wreck.

44
00:11:02,375 --> 00:11:05,276
Police had to drag it
to the pound.

45
00:11:05,311 --> 00:11:07,643
It's behind the station.

46
00:11:09,515 --> 00:11:11,415
After being bombarded
endlessly...

47
00:11:11,451 --> 00:11:13,578
by road safety propaganda,
it's...

48
00:11:15,855 --> 00:11:17,584
almost a relief to have...

49
00:11:19,125 --> 00:11:21,355
found myself
in an actual accident.

50
00:11:54,427 --> 00:11:56,418
Dr. Remington?

51
00:12:17,817 --> 00:12:18,806
James Ballard?

52
00:12:19,952 --> 00:12:21,442
Yes.

53
00:12:42,975 --> 00:12:43,999
Crash victim?

54
00:12:44,043 --> 00:12:46,341
Yes. I'd...

55
00:13:12,071 --> 00:13:14,062
We'll deal with these later.

56
00:13:36,762 --> 00:13:39,560
Both of the front wheels
of their car and the engine...

57
00:13:39,599 --> 00:13:42,466
were driven back
into the driver's section,

58
00:13:42,502 --> 00:13:44,629
pulling the floor.

59
00:13:47,473 --> 00:13:48,906
Blood still marked the hood...

60
00:13:48,941 --> 00:13:51,501
like little streamers
of black lace...

61
00:13:51,544 --> 00:13:54,274
running towards
the windshield wiper gutters.

62
00:13:55,414 --> 00:13:57,814
Bloody flecks were spattered...

63
00:13:57,850 --> 00:14:00,375
across the seat
and steering wheel.

64
00:14:04,023 --> 00:14:09,290
And the instrument panel
was buckled inwards...

65
00:14:09,328 --> 00:14:12,195
cracking the clock
and speedometer dials.

66
00:14:15,468 --> 00:14:18,164
The cabin was deformed.

67
00:14:19,172 --> 00:14:22,972
And there was dust and glass...

68
00:14:23,009 --> 00:14:25,876
and plastic flakes
everywhere inside.

69
00:14:28,014 --> 00:14:30,710
The carpeting was damp.

70
00:14:32,018 --> 00:14:35,977
It stank of blood and other body
and machine fluids.

71
00:15:01,781 --> 00:15:04,147
You should've gone
to the funeral.

72
00:15:05,284 --> 00:15:06,546
I wish I had.

73
00:15:08,754 --> 00:15:11,086
They bury the dead so quickly.

74
00:15:12,925 --> 00:15:15,655
They should leave them
lying around for months.

75
00:15:18,431 --> 00:15:20,228
What about his wife?
The woman doctor?

76
00:15:20,266 --> 00:15:22,200
Have you been to visit her yet?

77
00:15:23,936 --> 00:15:24,994
No.

78
00:15:27,440 --> 00:15:28,668
I couldn't.

79
00:15:32,945 --> 00:15:34,936
I feel too close to her.

80
00:16:07,980 --> 00:16:11,211
I don't like the idea of
your getting into a car so soon.

81
00:16:12,151 --> 00:16:13,675
I can't sit
on this balcony forever.

82
00:16:13,719 --> 00:16:16,017
I feel like a potted plant.

83
00:16:18,257 --> 00:16:20,248
How can you drive, James?

84
00:16:22,261 --> 00:16:24,161
You can barely walk.

85
00:16:26,799 --> 00:16:28,790
Is traffic heavier now?

86
00:16:31,470 --> 00:16:33,665
There seem to be
three times as many cars...

87
00:16:33,706 --> 00:16:35,936
as there were
before the accident.

88
00:16:37,643 --> 00:16:40,168
I have to leave for work.

89
00:19:19,271 --> 00:19:20,898
After this sort of thing...

90
00:19:20,940 --> 00:19:23,067
how do people manage
to look at a car...

91
00:19:23,108 --> 00:19:24,598
let alone drive one?

92
00:19:33,285 --> 00:19:35,617
I'm trying to find Charles' car.

93
00:19:38,290 --> 00:19:40,315
It's not here.

94
00:19:40,359 --> 00:19:42,793
Maybe the police
are still holding it.

95
00:19:42,828 --> 00:19:45,797
They said it was here.
They told me this morning.

96
00:19:56,976 --> 00:19:58,944
This is your car?

97
00:20:15,828 --> 00:20:17,796
You might tear your glove.

98
00:20:24,537 --> 00:20:27,631
I never should've come here.

99
00:20:27,673 --> 00:20:30,198
I'm surprised the police
don't make it more difficult.

100
00:20:31,377 --> 00:20:32,844
Were you badly hurt?

101
00:20:32,878 --> 00:20:35,346
I think we saw each other
at the hospital.

102
00:20:35,381 --> 00:20:37,406
I don't want the car.

103
00:20:38,083 --> 00:20:39,550
In fact,
I was appalled to find...

104
00:20:39,585 --> 00:20:42,645
that I have to pay
to have it scrapped.

105
00:20:44,890 --> 00:20:46,721
Can I give you a lift?

106
00:20:48,561 --> 00:20:51,155
I somehow find myself
driving again.

107
00:20:59,905 --> 00:21:02,465
You haven't told me
where we're going.

108
00:21:02,508 --> 00:21:03,736
I haven't?

109
00:21:05,344 --> 00:21:07,175
To the airport,
if you don't mind.

110
00:21:07,212 --> 00:21:08,509
The airport?

111
00:21:08,547 --> 00:21:10,310
Why? Are you leaving?

112
00:21:10,349 --> 00:21:11,680
Not yet.

113
00:21:12,685 --> 00:21:14,846
Though not soon enough
for some people.

114
00:21:15,354 --> 00:21:19,688
A death in the doctor's family
makes the patients uneasy.

115
00:21:19,725 --> 00:21:22,091
I take it you're not wearing
white to reassure them.

116
00:21:22,127 --> 00:21:25,187
I'll wear a fucking kimono
if I want to.

117
00:21:34,807 --> 00:21:36,798
So why the airport?

118
00:21:37,710 --> 00:21:39,803
I work in
the Immigration Department.

119
00:21:42,314 --> 00:21:43,872
Do you want a cigarette?

120
00:21:43,916 --> 00:21:45,076
No.

121
00:21:46,652 --> 00:21:49,120
I started to smoke
at the hospital.

122
00:21:50,623 --> 00:21:52,853
It's kind of stupid.

123
00:22:02,801 --> 00:22:05,463
Look at all this traffic.

124
00:22:09,241 --> 00:22:10,503
I'm not sure I can deal with it.

125
00:22:10,542 --> 00:22:12,942
It's much worse now.
Have you noticed that?

126
00:22:12,978 --> 00:22:14,036
Yes.

127
00:22:22,187 --> 00:22:24,178
The day I left the hospital...

128
00:22:25,858 --> 00:22:29,453
I had the extraordinary
feeling that all these cars...

129
00:22:29,495 --> 00:22:31,986
were gathering
for some special reason...

130
00:22:32,031 --> 00:22:33,464
I didn't understand.

131
00:22:35,367 --> 00:22:39,428
There seemed to be
ten times as much traffic.

132
00:22:45,277 --> 00:22:46,676
Are we imagining it?

133
00:22:53,118 --> 00:22:56,110
You've bought yourself
exactly the same car again.

134
00:22:57,723 --> 00:23:00,248
It's the same shape and color.

135
00:23:25,084 --> 00:23:27,245
We're close
to the airport garage.

136
00:23:27,920 --> 00:23:30,252
It won't be busy
this time of day.

137
00:26:21,159 --> 00:26:23,286
These were
the confident last words...

138
00:26:23,328 --> 00:26:26,991
of the brilliant, young
Hollywood star James Dean...

139
00:26:28,500 --> 00:26:32,459
as he piloted his Porsche
550 Spyder race car...

140
00:26:32,504 --> 00:26:35,632
toward a date with death...

141
00:26:35,674 --> 00:26:37,801
along a lonely stretch...

142
00:26:37,843 --> 00:26:40,641
of California
two-lane blacktop...

143
00:26:40,679 --> 00:26:42,874
Route 466.

144
00:26:46,718 --> 00:26:50,210
"Don't worry.
That guy's gotta see us. "

145
00:26:57,195 --> 00:27:00,289
The year... 1955.

146
00:27:01,800 --> 00:27:04,530
The day... September 30.

147
00:27:06,471 --> 00:27:07,631
The time...

148
00:27:09,474 --> 00:27:11,271
Now.

149
00:27:15,213 --> 00:27:19,343
The first star of our show
is "Little Bastard. "

150
00:27:20,452 --> 00:27:22,647
James Dean's racing Porsche.

151
00:27:23,722 --> 00:27:25,383
He named it after himself...

152
00:27:25,424 --> 00:27:29,326
and had his racing number...
130... painted on it.

153
00:27:31,596 --> 00:27:33,621
Who is that, the announcer?
Do I know him?

154
00:27:33,665 --> 00:27:35,132
Here behind the seats was...

155
00:27:35,167 --> 00:27:39,467
a very sophisticated air-cooled
four-cylinder racing engine.

156
00:27:39,504 --> 00:27:43,235
That's Vaughan.
He spoke to you at the hospital.

157
00:27:46,878 --> 00:27:48,573
I thought he was
a medical photographer...

158
00:27:51,817 --> 00:27:53,375
doing some sort of
accident research.

159
00:27:53,418 --> 00:27:56,387
He wanted every conceivable
detail about our crash.

160
00:27:56,421 --> 00:27:59,879
Body... light,
no more than 1,350 pounds.

161
00:27:59,925 --> 00:28:03,156
It was nimble.
It was responsive.

162
00:28:03,195 --> 00:28:05,527
When I first met Vaughan,
he was a specialist...

163
00:28:05,564 --> 00:28:07,657
in international
computerized traffic systems.

164
00:28:07,699 --> 00:28:09,667
The racers of the day...

165
00:28:09,701 --> 00:28:12,670
said that it was not
an easy car to drive fast.

166
00:28:12,704 --> 00:28:14,672
I don't know what he is now.

167
00:28:14,706 --> 00:28:17,675
Which brings us
to the second star...

168
00:28:17,709 --> 00:28:21,839
a stunt man, former
race driver Colin Seagrave.

169
00:28:21,880 --> 00:28:23,370
Colin Seagrave.

170
00:28:24,783 --> 00:28:27,877
He will drive our replica
of James Dean's car.

171
00:28:32,557 --> 00:28:34,752
How you doing?
Sure you're up for this?

172
00:28:35,794 --> 00:28:38,194
You bet.

173
00:28:38,230 --> 00:28:41,859
I myself shall play the role
of Dean's racing mechanic...

174
00:28:41,900 --> 00:28:45,358
Rolf Voudrich, sent over
from the Porsche factory...

175
00:28:45,404 --> 00:28:47,031
in Zuffenhausen, Germany.

176
00:28:47,072 --> 00:28:49,870
Now, this mechanic
was himself fated to die...

177
00:28:49,908 --> 00:28:53,241
in a car crash in Germany
26 years later.

178
00:28:55,080 --> 00:28:57,173
The third,
and in some ways...

179
00:28:58,350 --> 00:29:01,410
most important player...

180
00:29:01,453 --> 00:29:05,253
the college student,
Donald Turnipseed...

181
00:29:05,290 --> 00:29:08,726
played by movie stunt man
Brett Trask.

182
00:29:11,129 --> 00:29:13,063
Brett Trask.

183
00:29:18,637 --> 00:29:23,506
Turnipseed was on his way home
to Fresno for the weekend.

184
00:29:23,542 --> 00:29:27,342
James Dean was on his way to
an automobile race in Salinas.

185
00:29:28,647 --> 00:29:31,810
Salinas was just a dusty town
in Northern California.

186
00:29:33,151 --> 00:29:37,281
The two would meet
for one moment.

187
00:29:37,322 --> 00:29:40,849
But it was a moment that...

188
00:29:41,860 --> 00:29:44,488
that would create
a Hollywood legend.

189
00:29:46,631 --> 00:29:48,861
You'll notice that
we're not wearing helmets...

190
00:29:48,900 --> 00:29:51,095
or safety padding of any kind.

191
00:29:51,136 --> 00:29:54,594
Our cars are not equipped
with roll cages or seat belts.

192
00:29:54,639 --> 00:29:59,599
We rely solely on the skill
of our drivers for our safety...

193
00:29:59,644 --> 00:30:03,671
so that we can bring you
the ultimate in authenticity.

194
00:30:06,184 --> 00:30:07,173
All right.

195
00:30:08,353 --> 00:30:12,119
Here we go...
the fatal crash of James Dean.

196
00:30:20,732 --> 00:30:22,029
OK, let's wind her up.

197
00:30:39,751 --> 00:30:40,740
Go.

198
00:31:38,910 --> 00:31:41,242
Is this part of the act,
or are they really hurt?

199
00:31:41,279 --> 00:31:42,746
I don't know.

200
00:31:42,781 --> 00:31:45,272
You can never
be sure with Vaughan.

201
00:31:46,785 --> 00:31:48,275
This is his show.

202
00:31:52,123 --> 00:31:54,921
Rolf Voudrich...

203
00:31:54,960 --> 00:31:57,793
was thrown from the Porsche...

204
00:31:58,964 --> 00:32:00,522
and spent a year...

205
00:32:02,234 --> 00:32:03,724
in the hospital...

206
00:32:07,405 --> 00:32:10,238
recovering from his injuries.

207
00:32:19,251 --> 00:32:23,210
Donald Turnipseed
was found wandering around...

208
00:32:23,255 --> 00:32:25,416
in a daze but basically unhurt.

209
00:32:26,925 --> 00:32:29,894
James Dean
died of a broken neck...

210
00:32:29,928 --> 00:32:31,919
and became immortal.

211
00:32:39,337 --> 00:32:40,827
What's the matter?

212
00:32:42,040 --> 00:32:45,840
Hold me up. I'm dizzy.
I can't stand.

213
00:32:45,877 --> 00:32:48,345
I know that man... Seagrave.

214
00:32:48,380 --> 00:32:50,371
I think he's genuinely hurt.

215
00:32:58,590 --> 00:33:00,285
Disperse at once.

216
00:33:07,832 --> 00:33:09,493
You're all liable for fines
or arrest.

217
00:33:11,503 --> 00:33:14,734
Disperse at once.

218
00:33:19,778 --> 00:33:21,746
- How you doin'?
- I'm all right.

219
00:33:23,248 --> 00:33:24,579
What's the matter with Seagrave?

220
00:33:24,616 --> 00:33:28,848
He hit his head, I think.
His balance is off.

221
00:33:32,023 --> 00:33:34,821
Why are the police
taking this so seriously?

222
00:33:34,859 --> 00:33:36,793
No, it's not the police.

223
00:33:36,828 --> 00:33:39,820
It's the Department
of Transport.

224
00:33:39,864 --> 00:33:41,331
It's a big joke.

225
00:33:41,366 --> 00:33:44,358
They have no idea
who we really are.

226
00:33:59,317 --> 00:34:00,682
Was I glib?

227
00:34:02,153 --> 00:34:05,645
"James Dean died of a broken
neck and became immortal. "

228
00:34:11,496 --> 00:34:12,986
I couldn't resist.

229
00:34:54,639 --> 00:34:56,106
Oh, God.

230
00:34:56,141 --> 00:34:58,166
What happened?

231
00:34:58,209 --> 00:35:01,372
Come here. Lie down.

232
00:35:01,413 --> 00:35:03,938
